  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Will a misdemeanor warrant in one state apply on another state?",
  "response": "Yes, a misdemeanor warrant issued in one state can generally be enforced in another state. This is due to the **Interstate Compact on the Out-of-State Parolee Supervision (also known as the Interstate Compact)** and other agreements between states that facilitate the enforcement of warrants across state lines.\n\nHere\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Extradition**: If you are located in another state and law enforcement becomes aware of the warrant, they may arrest you. Whether you will be extradited back to the state that issued the warrant depends on the seriousness of the offense, the distance between the states, and the policies of the involved jurisdictions. For misdemeanors, extradition may be less common unless the state is willing to incur the expense or the offense is significant.\n\n2. **National Crime Information Center (NCIC)**: Warrants are often entered into the NCIC database, which is accessible to law enforcement agencies nationwide. If you are stopped or interact with law enforcement in another state, they may discover the warrant.\n\n3. **Voluntary Surrender**: In some cases, you may be allowed to voluntarily return to the state where the warrant was issued to resolve the matter without formal extradition.\n\nIf you believe there is a warrant for your arrest in another state, it is advisable to consult with an attorney to understand your rights and the best course of action. Ignoring the warrant can lead to more serious consequences.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
